Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the Agency, it was the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had entered into close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to outer space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always find understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw astronomical observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled " Introduction to astronomy ".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the cold listeners and in later years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld was awarded in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his work "Introduction to the Astronautique".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a world-renowned astronomical propagator, his contribution has been rewarded, in particular, by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a dam was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or to slow down the raisin.
The only known information on this root was that of the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
The research was conducted by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the records that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
The purpose of these two projects was military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all the projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Comitéet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works dedicated to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to Polish astronomical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November 1954 issue of the Journal Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronomy
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the area of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and since the fall the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, PTA's first president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters was 80 cm long and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was built, RM-1A and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-storey RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all the development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded in the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litre, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 litre and in Meteor-1C it was 0.62 litre.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, and the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR national committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the Miroslaw Hermaszewski pilot became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on works of public utility.
This decision raised a serious debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems geared to liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This actually means that the different economic entities and national economic systems are permanently in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of freedom of trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with a frightful financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) generate pressure on prices.
The following meaning must be put to the end: a producer is striving by importing goods sold below to resist economic competition by "making the price of the competitor more expensive", with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thereby increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either to transfer production abroad, to buy cheaply, or to disappear. The result is a significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and hence responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the State are necessarily increasing.
All of this intensifies the perfect will of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole society by this race for the benefit.
This situation is at such a public level that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of different countries are forced to engage in a mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments place their own population at the expense of private capital, regardless of the social collapse.
This is most evident in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to compel its own population economically to accept the private capital price diktat, particularly in the field of wages.
This occurs on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and by the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour law.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the gap between the rich and the poor.
In RFA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot meet their needs with their own work.
The number of these people is already estimated by millions.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is obliged to pay an additional to achieve the vital minimum.
Such a scandal has, for example, been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the Member States of the south of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that private capital will one day invest in their country.
