Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution because it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being overly critical of Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain when voting on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are therefore facing several fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I think they're still trying to find this role, but they're on the road to a 'more normal' foreign policy.
An external policy, such as France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany has to protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position with regard to the conflict in the Near East and the abstention from the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to undermine public opinion, but also the elites of Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a key element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus shown that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, views on the Palestinian initiative vary.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from overwhelming enthusiasm for Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore form part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing at the moment in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will play a role as a locomotive in the future and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, particularly because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been delicate.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that makes them more independent.
Does Germany see itself playing a major role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty in taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable for obvious reasons, and the country still faces difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look at, for example, the euro crisis, we note that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for Germans.
In fact, this is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of very diverse neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment, the EU does not fill this vacuum, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they don't like it any less, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute where academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
