Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and blennorrhagia (or gonorrhea).
Current STIs include HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubis pux and gale belong to the parasitic IST.
Which groups are primarily concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhagia often appear in men who have sexual relations with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is the origin of at least four cases of syphilis out of five reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungic), bleinnorrhagia and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, about 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15-25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis more than doubled in 10 years: the figure rose from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has decreased.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a one-tenth decrease over the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genital organs, urinary pain, white loss, low wind pain, and the appearance of buttons and warts.
However, they do not cause any pain or other symptoms on a regular basis and therefore remain hidden.
How do you protect yourself?
Preservatives may reduce the risk of infection, but do not protect 100%.
The reason is that pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases may also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close body contact.
The experts therefore recommend that any person who often changes sex partners should regularly pass examinations.
Most rapidly-disciplined ISTs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
