Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecutors said.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning would have been subjected to during detention.
The trial concerns Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to classify the case on the grounds that the kidnapping of Manning took place in extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to prove, Friday, that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the biggest leak of confidential information in the entire history of the U.S. Army -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claimed to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints regarding his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a petition demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping was carried out under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- occurred one day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At the Friday hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms that officers had completed after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms, on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he had been given to his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had in prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, stated Fein.
Manning replied that he had voiced concerns about certain problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but did not address the issues raised.
"They wrote "no problem" (after addressing the concerns), and yet, it did not mean that I had not raised any problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status amended indicating a "hazard of injury".
The military stated that they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was going well, and I wanted to be removed from this status... in order to enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he had considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and had fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept aware of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent the most clear of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were a mattress, blanket, tongs, clothing and glasses.
He tried to stay on the move, because sleeping or lying down during the day was contrary to the regulation.
Manning also specified that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned at night, they would wake him up so he could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge also asked Manning about an allegation reported in his Thursday testimony -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell at Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that, at no time, he was allowed to cover himself with cover during the call.
During the judge's questions, on Friday, Manning stated that he had deducted from his guard's order that he should release his cover that could have hidden his nudity, but he recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, because he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning would have told the officer that he could have used the elasticity of his slip or his tongs to hurt himself, but he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, tongs, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that at least the judge would take into account the experiences he had experienced during his detention and that he would significantly reduce his sentence if he had to be found guilty before a court of martial, a trial that should be held early next year.
The defence stated that Manning intends to plead guilty of the least serious crimes and to fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed to be too extreme.
The hearing should resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges brought against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defence.
If all the charges are held, he will be sentenced to life in criminal detention.
