The hardest job in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas emanating from the ends of the earth solidifies to the contact of the air.
After harvesting large rocks of sulphur, which weigh almost 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano that peaks at 2.386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to gravigate this distance, at a tortoise allure, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall in the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Minors in Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extract.
Once on top, he took a path between the tourists who photographed them as though they were circus animals, and barely carrying the heavy baskets, they walked the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company had set up a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, you can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to 10,000 rupees (83 cents euros) to the petrochemical industry as this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to manufacture candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to whiten sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," Anto explains, who generally makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and he is exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11,50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what it would gain in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", says the carrier who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as indisputable as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Then he suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur has already begun to pay him the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
