The summit of Unasur ended without the release of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the release of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
EE tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the summit was closed, and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government's website.
When they were questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
Journalists' access to summit information has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The limited information circulated among journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of the presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who called for more important information.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an electronic mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not of the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd Arab South- Pays Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was urgently requested by the press, it had also not circulated the declaration also known as the Lima Declaration, as had been previously announced.
On the ASPA official website, it can be verified that the document was published in March last year.
In both international meetings, Peruvian authorities have tried to establish secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which separates a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and declared that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleadings of both parties in the trial that Lima tried against Santiago and which starts on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and implement the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are facing today before this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chili has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," President Piñera added by handing out to President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced this week the Bogota Covenant by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua, which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the outcome document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been established among South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would set up "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve drug accessibility, low-price Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our people," said President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although it did not provide any further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation of Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow for its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and well-connected with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos declared, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to review all these tracks, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with Nicaragua," he said.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful manner possible," said President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to assist the takeover of power of the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, at the summit, the Ministers of Defence of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru has the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
