AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed as a result of the test: HIV positive.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said by referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it and his strain was such as he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit in Guadalajara civilian hospital (HCG), in which he met in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, little choice of treatment and more stigmats.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic prevented him from saying goodbye "because he was voiceless."
At the time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, in all cases after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said HCG's head of HIV unit Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of allocation of the immune system that patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not consume drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years for those reaching a rate of 500 CD4.
Simply speaking, it means that for someone who would receive a positive HIV diagnosis at 25 years of age, "if he remains under control, he can live without problems up to 75 years," the scientist asked.
In order to restore this progress in its context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While mortality has significantly decreased in recent years, in Mexico, the number of people who died after AIDS has increased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients with national data have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we have never missed drugs, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or then they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, which is necessary to have a greater impact on overall mortality, it is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, for this, it is necessary to offer mass testing tests to all those who request it."
Specialists and members of the State AIDS Prevention Council of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on its proposal, as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do their screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his youth, he was already a AIDS carrier and suffered from the sarcoma of Kaposi, a cancer tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better that I break up three times a week," they say, that's not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I do exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he is suffering from cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sexual life, but co-responsibly, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
If they do the test, if they take risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Preservatives on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to it, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are giving them packages of a hundred, it is very good, but as a result, that today still, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do?", posed with sarcasm and valuable judgments by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that adolescents do not want to hear, says the journalist.
It proposes reorientating this ineffective distribution; that condoms not only be sold to counters, but are found in public toilet distributors and in places where young people live.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor was it a matter of paying the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had said when asked whether there would be a distribution of condoms in his administration.
"This is not how sexuality works, it is best to provide condoms to people already sexually active," he said.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The State is the 4th State of the country in number of new and accumulated cases of AIDS and 13th cases for the number of HIV patients.
92% of the contaminations are sexually, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatally.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each case, there are 4 or 5 people who are unaware of it.
