Hector "Hetin" Reyes "The basketball is my whole life"
The world-trotter of basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as large as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I've worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
"The basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his unstandard itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s to 1982, after having spent 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
"It was my best years, the ones I enjoyed most because I had the chance to take part in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a great deal of satisfaction for many years, including the five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
Then I retired at the 1981 championship, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been the leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, "I have a Costa Rican player for you, he measures two meters.
