That's how Mincy, one of Puerto Rico's best players, started.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember he was saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse was going to help us try to win another one.
He welcomed the Vaqueros Championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manito of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of Mincy's and Mincy's duties on the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre- Olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us play the last game, Reyes said.
Is the World Team 1990 the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is that of the Cuban Pan-American Games in 1991, when we won the gold and we ran into the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
