A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when Stuart Charmé's professor of religion decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible trap: the end of the "great count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, which many refer to as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what expected him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax gulf that some called "the debt armageddon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists at the end of time thought the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we told it, it was a very good time.
And remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of State of Pennsylvania, the History Professor of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an Assistant Professor of History of Art and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply called "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "near disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the State of Pennsylvania, the final examination will be made on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
Courses have proved to be quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, composed of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the start of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
